\par Path_corner spawnflags can be used to provide further information.
\par 
\par REVERSE\tab Rotate in the opposite direction.
\par X_AXIS\tab \tab Rotate about the X axis.
\par Y_AXIS\tab \tab Rotate about the Y axis.
\par 
\par If neither X nor Y is specified, Z is assumed to be the axis of rotation.
\par 
\par Translation is controlled the same way it is for func_trains. The func_rotrain has a \lquote speed\rquote  key and the distance travelled depends on the placement of the path_corners.
\par 
\par Func_rotrains can be triggered on and off. If you trigger in the middle of a rotation, the rotation is paused u
ntil triggered again. At that point, it will complete the original rotation arc for styles 3,4,5. It will continue a constant rotation for style 2.
\par 
\par It\rquote s best for complex combinations of func_rotrains to team them together. You cannot team func_trains or f
unc_rotatings with func_rotrains. The triggering on/off code is too complex to mix these entities together. Simply use a style 1 func_rotrain where you would use a func_train, and a style 2 func_rotrain between 2 path_corners that are coincident for a fun
c_rotating.
\par 
